---
import DocLayout from '../../layouts/DocLayout.astro';
import PropsTable from '../../components/PropsTable.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import StorybookPreview from '../../components/StorybookPreview.astro';
import LiveButtonDemo from '../../components/react/LiveButtonDemo';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL || '/storyhouse-design-system/';
const currentPath = `${base}components/button`;
---

<DocLayout
  title="Button"
  status="stable"
  description="Versatile button component with multiple variants, sizes, and states. Supports loading, icons, and full-width layouts."
>
  <section>
    <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
    <p>
      The <code>Button</code> component is the primary action trigger in the design system. It supports multiple visual variants,
      three sizes, loading state, and full-width mode. Every button is built with accessibility as a first-class concern —
      focus-visible rings, proper ARIA attributes, and keyboard navigation are built in.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 id="live-demo">Live Demo</h2>
    <p>Click the buttons below to see the component in action. The loading button simulates a 2-second async operation.</p>
    <div class="my-6 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm dark:border-gray-800 dark:bg-gray-900">
      <LiveButtonDemo client:load />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 id="variants">Variants</h2>
    <p>
      Buttons come in four visual variants to match different levels of emphasis and purpose.
    </p>

    <div class="my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm dark:border-gray-800 dark:bg-gray-900">
      <button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-orange-600 px-4 py-2 text-base font-medium text-white transition-colors hover:bg-orange-700 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-orange-600 focus-visible:ring-offset-2">Primary</button>
      <button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-gray-200 px-4 py-2 text-base font-medium text-gray-900 transition-colors hover:bg-gray-300 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-gray-400 focus-visible:ring-offset-2">Secondary</button>
      <button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-transparent px-4 py-2 text-base font-medium text-gray-700 transition-colors hover:bg-gray-100 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-gray-400 focus-visible:ring-offset-2">Ghost</button>
      <button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-red-600 px-4 py-2 text-base font-medium text-white transition-colors hover:bg-red-700 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-red-600 focus-visible:ring-offset-2">Danger</button>
    </div>

    <CodeBlock title="button-variants.tsx" code={`import { Button } from '@storyhouse/components';

export function ButtonVariants() {
  return (
    <div className="flex gap-3">
      <Button variant="primary">Primary</Button>
      <Button variant="secondary">Secondary</Button>
      <Button variant="ghost">Ghost</Button>
      <Button variant="danger">Danger</Button>
    </div>
  );
}`} />
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 id="sizes">Sizes</h2>
    <p>Three sizes cover most use cases: small for tight spaces, medium as the default, and large for primary CTAs.</p>

    <div class="my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm dark:border-gray-800 dark:bg-gray-900">
      <button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-orange-600 px-3 py-1.5 text-sm font-medium text-white transition-colors hover:bg-orange-700">Small</button>
      <button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-orange-600 px-4 py-2 text-base font-medium text-white transition-colors hover:bg-orange-700">Medium</button>
      <button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-orange-600 px-6 py-3 text-lg font-medium text-white transition-colors hover:bg-orange-700">Large</button>
    </div>

    <CodeBlock title="button-sizes.tsx" code={`import { Button } from '@storyhouse/components';

export function ButtonSizes() {
  return (
    <div className="flex items-center gap-3">
      <Button size="sm">Small</Button>
      <Button size="md">Medium</Button>
      <Button size="lg">Large</Button>
    </div>
  );
}`} />
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 id="loading">Loading State</h2>
    <p>
      The <code>isLoading</code> prop shows a spinner and disables interaction, which is critical for async actions
      like form submissions or API calls to prevent duplicate operations.
    </p>

    <div class="my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm dark:border-gray-800 dark:bg-gray-900">
      <button disabled="" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-orange-600 px-4 py-2 text-base font-medium text-white opacity-50 pointer-events-none"><span class="mr-2 h-4 w-4 animate-spin rounded-full border-2 border-current border-t-transparent"></span>Saving...</button>
    </div>

    <CodeBlock title="button-loading.tsx" code={`import { Button } from '@storyhouse/components';

export function ButtonLoading() {
  return (
    <Button isLoading>
      Saving...
    </Button>
  );
}`} />
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 id="full-width">Full Width</h2>
    <p>Use <code>fullWidth</code> for buttons that should span their container — ideal for mobile layouts and form submissions.</p>

    <div class="my-6 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm dark:border-gray-800 dark:bg-gray-900">
      <button class="w-full inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-orange-600 px-4 py-2 text-base font-medium text-white transition-colors hover:bg-orange-700">Submit</button>
    </div>

    <CodeBlock title="button-fullwidth.tsx" code={`import { Button } from '@storyhouse/components';

export function ButtonFullWidth() {
  return (
    <Button fullWidth>
      Submit
    </Button>
  );
}`} />
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 id="disabled">Disabled State</h2>

    <div class="my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm dark:border-gray-800 dark:bg-gray-900">
      <button disabled="" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-orange-600 px-4 py-2 text-base font-medium text-white opacity-50 pointer-events-none">Cannot Click</button>
    </div>

    <CodeBlock title="button-disabled.tsx" code={`import { Button } from '@storyhouse/components';

export function ButtonDisabled() {
  return (
    <Button disabled>
      Cannot Click
    </Button>
  );
}`} />
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 id="props">Props</h2>
    <PropsTable
      rows={[
        { name: 'variant', type: '"primary" | "secondary" | "ghost" | "danger"', default: '"primary"', description: 'Visual style variant for different emphasis levels.' },
        { name: 'size', type: '"sm" | "md" | "lg"', default: '"md"', description: 'Button size. Use sm for compact UIs, lg for primary CTAs.' },
        { name: 'isLoading', type: 'boolean', default: 'false', description: 'Shows a spinner and disables interaction during async operations.' },
        { name: 'fullWidth', type: 'boolean', default: 'false', description: 'Makes the button span 100% of its parent container width.' },
        { name: 'disabled', type: 'boolean', default: 'false', description: 'Disables the button, reducing opacity and preventing interaction.' },
        { name: 'className', type: 'string', default: '-', description: 'Additional CSS classes to merge with default styles (uses tailwind-merge).' },
        { name: 'children', type: 'React.ReactNode', default: '-', description: 'Content to render inside the button. Can include icons or text.' },
      ]}
    />
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 id="edge-cases">Edge Cases &amp; Error States</h2>

    <h3>Icon-Only Buttons (No Children Text)</h3>
    <p>
      When using Button with only an icon and no visible children, always provide an <code>aria-label</code>
      so screen readers can convey the action. The button maintains proper focus-visible ring styling
      even without text content.
    </p>

    <CodeBlock title="button-icon-only.tsx" code={`import { Button } from '@storyhouse/components';

export function IconOnlyButton() {
  return (
    <Button variant="ghost" aria-label="Delete item">
      <svg className="h-5 w-5" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth={2}>
        <path strokeLinecap="round" strokeLinejoin="round" d="M19 7l-.867 12.142A2 2 0 0116.138 21H7.862a2 2 0 01-1.995-1.858L5 7m5 4v6m4-6v6m1-10V4a1 1 0 00-1-1h-4a1 1 0 00-1 1v3M4 7h16" />
      </svg>
    </Button>
  );
}`} />

    <h3>Long Button Text</h3>
    <p>
      Buttons do not truncate text. Long labels will wrap to multiple lines inside the button.
      If you need a fixed-width button, set a <code>className</code> with <code>whitespace-nowrap</code> to prevent wrapping.
    </p>

    <CodeBlock title="button-long-text.tsx" code={`import { Button } from '@storyhouse/components';

export function LongTextButton() {
  return (
    <>
      {/* Wraps naturally */}
      <Button variant="secondary">Save all changes and continue editing later</Button>

      {/* Force single line */}
      <Button className="whitespace-nowrap">Save all changes</Button>
    </>
  );
}`} />

    <h3>FullWidth Inside Flex Containers</h3>
    <p>
      When a <code>fullWidth</code> button is inside a flex container with <code>flex-wrap</code>, it will
      stretch to fill the parent width. This works as expected for mobile layouts but can cause
      unexpected stretching in complex grid or flex arrangements.
    </p>

    <CodeBlock title="button-fullwidth-flex.tsx" code={`import { Button } from '@storyhouse/components';

export function FullWidthInFlex() {
  return (
    <div className="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
      <Button fullWidth>This spans the entire flex row</Button>
      <Button>Compact</Button>
    </div>
  );
}`} />

    <h3>Loading + Disabled Interaction</h3>
    <p>
      When <code>isLoading</code> is <code>true</code>, the button is automatically disabled regardless
      of the <code>disabled</code> prop value. This prevents double-submission during async operations
      even if both props are accidentally passed.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 id="best-practices">Best Practices &amp; Usage Guidelines</h2>

    <h3>Variant Selection</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Primary</strong> — The main call-to-action. Use at most one per view or form.</li>
      <li><strong>Secondary</strong> — For alternative actions alongside a primary button. Pair with primary in dialogs and modals.</li>
      <li><strong>Ghost</strong> — For subtle actions like "Cancel" or "Edit". Good in card headers and toolbars.</li>
      <li><strong>Danger</strong> — For destructive actions (delete, remove, archive). Never use for primary CTAs.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Form Integration</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Always set <code>type="submit"</code> when Button is inside a form</li>
      <li>Use <code>isLoading</code> during form submission to prevent double-submission</li>
      <li>Place the primary action button on the left, secondary on the right in dialog footers</li>
      <li>Use <code>fullWidth</code> on mobile viewports; constrain width with <code>max-w-xs</code> on desktop</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Accessibility</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Button uses a native <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> element — keyboard navigation (Enter/Space) is built-in</li>
      <li>The <code>focus-visible</code> ring only shows for keyboard users, not mouse clicks</li>
      <li>When using icon-only buttons, always provide <code>aria-label</code></li>
      <li>Loading state disables the button automatically so screen readers announce it as disabled</li>
      <li>All color variants maintain WCAG AA contrast ratios (4.5:1 for text)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 id="implementation">Implementation Details</h2>

    <h3>Component Architecture</h3>
    <p>
      Button uses <code>React.forwardRef</code> to pass the ref to the underlying native <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> element,
      enabling parent components to focus the button programmatically or use it with tooltip/popper libraries.
      <code>displayName</code> is set for React DevTools debugging.
    </p>

    <h3>ClassName Merging</h3>
    <p>
      The component uses <code>cn()</code> (a <code>tailwind-merge</code> + <code>clsx</code> wrapper from
      <code>@storyhouse/utils</code>) to merge the consumer's <code>className</code> prop with internal styles.
      This resolves Tailwind class conflicts automatically — if you pass <code>className="bg-red-500"</code>,
      it overrides the default variant background while preserving all other computed classes.
    </p>

    <h3>Dark Mode</h3>
    <p>
      Button uses Tailwind dark mode variants (<code>dark:</code> prefix) on color classes.
      This means all four variants automatically adapt in dark mode without any prop changes or JS logic.
      Dark mode is driven by the <code>class</code> strategy on the <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> element.
    </p>

    <h3>Loading State Architecture</h3>
    <p>
      When <code>isLoading</code> is enabled, an animated spinner element is rendered before children.
      The spinner uses <code>animate-spin</code> with a Tailwind border trick (transparent top border).
      All animations respect the <code>prefers-reduced-motion</code> media query via the globals.css override.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 id="accessibility">Accessibility</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Uses native <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> element for correct keyboard semantics</li>
      <li>Focus-visible ring styles ensure keyboard users see focus indicators</li>
      <li>Disabled state reduces opacity and removes pointer events</li>
      <li>Loading state prevents double-submission of forms</li>
      <li>Spinner animation respects <code>prefers-reduced-motion</code></li>
      <li>Button text is clearly readable for all color variants (high contrast ratio)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 id="storybook-preview">Interactive Preview</h2>
    <p>Explore all Button variants and props interactively in Storybook:</p>
    <StorybookPreview id="components-button--primary" title="Button — Storybook" height="500" />
  </section>
</DocLayout>
